39;s just fantastic.</p><p> So that&#39;s one of the fun things about it is you just, anyone can listen.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So curve ball question. What&#39;s your favorite podcast guest story that you can tell publicly? Because we all have great stories, some of which not really FCC approved.</p><p> SEIDES: There are one or two of those, but not that many. I think I would even go all the way back to my very first episode. So it was with Steve Galbraith, who we mentioned earlier with Jack Bogle. And it was just this idea, I knew Steve, I knew he had a great story, and I sat down and recorded it. And I couldn&#39;t find the recording on the recording device after we finished.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: (LAUGH)</p><p> SEIDES: And it was so good, I just said, I can&#39;t wait to share this with people. And then I thought that that was the end of my podcast career after the first recording. And it took a good friend of mine, who&#39;s a technical whiz to figure out, which actually wasn&#39;t that hard, I just didn&#39;t know how to do it, to extract the conversation from the recording device.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I&#39;m going to share a similar story with you. So normally I&#39;m in the Bloomberg studios. I got an engineer, I got all the latest equipment. I have the easiest gig in podcast. I show up, I said, “Hey, print this out for me, off we go.” One about five years ago, I&#39;m planning a trip to Silicon Valley. I tee up two interviews in a day, Mark Andreessen of Andreessen Horowitz and Nobel Laureate Bill Sharpe. And by coincidence, I couldn&#39;t find a place to record the Bill Sharp interview, Andreessen said, “Oh, do it here. “You could use our podcast studios.” They were great. So I sit down with Bill, so I do Andreessen in the morning, right? In the afternoon is Bill Sharp, after lunch. I sit down, I have my device, which the engineer has taught me 47 times how to do, and I start the podcast with Bill Sharp, and maybe 90 seconds in, I notice I&#39;m not recording.</p><p> And I just have my stomach sinks. And I imagine spending an hour and a half with Bill Sharp and not having it record. So I&#39;m like, “Bill, I&#39;m not getting a good audio level. “Let&#39;s start this again.” So I hit it and now the red light&#39;s on, the view meter&#39;s going crazy, and I could see it&#39;s recording. I go, “Let&#39;s start over. “I think you were too soft.” And I just adjust it and we do the recording. And to me, that was the nightmare scenario of missing, God, Nobel Laureate, imagine that. So you found the Galbraith…</p><p> SEIDES: Found the recording, went out, and the rest is history.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So that&#39;s really interesting. So we only have you for so much time, and I appreciate you tolerating my nonsense.</p><p> Let&#39;s jump to my favorite questions that I ask all of my guests, some of which I think I&#39;m ready to retire. Probably the first one I&#39;m ready to retire, which is a post-lockdown question. I was asking people, hey, what are you streaming? What&#39;s keeping you entertained during lockdown?</p><p> Let&#39;s see if you have an answer to that. What have you been watching that&#39;s interesting?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I&#39;m a Ted Lasso guy, and I&#39;ve watched the finale of the last season three times.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I thought that was unfairly slagged. It was really good.</p><p> SEIDES: It was really good. So in addition to that, I had on the show last year a guy named Brent Montgomery, and Brent&#39;s a TV producer. He created Pawn Stars and Duck Dynasty. His latest show is called The King of Collectibles.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES: And it&#39;s Pawn Stars meets sports. The guy named Ken Golden, who&#39;s one of the largest sports collectibles dealers.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES: And it is so, so good.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Do you get into the massive amount of counterfeit crap that&#39;s in that space at all? Because I would, of all the junk I buy, sports collectibles is the last thing in the world I would ever risk a penny on. I&#39;m convinced there&#39;s some kid in some sweatshop in a basement signing Michael Jordan&#39;s name over and over again.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, they do show how they go through the authentication process, at least with this one very high quality dealer.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, I mean, I&#39;m sure there are ways to authenticate it, but every time I look at something on eBay, I just kind of like look it and go, no way.</p><p> SEIDES: This has, you know, it has Mike Tyson on it, it has all these incredible athletes and entertainers that get involved with this guy. It&#39;s a fantastic show.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really, that sounds really, really interesting.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk about books. You&#39;ve written two of them. What are some of the favorite books that you&#39;ve read and what are you reading currently?</p><p> SEIDES: This year, the favorite book I&#39;ve read is “Unreasonable Hospitality.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I just got that book. Somebody recommended it. It looks fascinating.</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s by Will Guidara, who&#39;s one of the founders of Eleven Madison, Danny Meyer&#39;s partner, and really describes in excruciating, thoughtful detail what it takes to be a creative customer, a customer-focused organization. It&#39;s a phenomenal book.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: For a long time, Eleven Madison was just, you know, Michelin rated, everything else. It was spectacular.</p><p> SEIDES: So that&#39;s my favorite one this year. The one I&#39;ve been reading most recently, which has been a long project before I go to bed, and it&#39;s a 10-year-old book, is Bill Simmons&#39; “Book of Basketball.”</p><p> So Bill Simmons wrote a book that ranked the top 100 basketball players, as again, 10 years ago, of all time, using both stats and his incredible knowledge and judgment, and it is addictive and incredibly fun.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So spoiler, was it Jordan or LeBron? Who does he rank as number one?</p><p> SEIDES: I&#39;m only up to 25, which is Bill Walton.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So you don&#39;t know.</p><p> SEIDES: I don&#39;t know yet.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And you know, 10 years ago, was Curry really on the list?</p><p> SEIDES: So early on in the book, he had this tiered system and he talked about the players that weren&#39;t yet on it. And Curry was mentioned as one he didn&#39;t think would get onto the list in a future edition.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Hilarious, right? And now he&#39;s probably top 10, right? Is that a fair statement?</p><p> Last two questions. What sort of advice would you give to a recent college graduate interested in a career in either alternative investments, allocation, anything finance related?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, the general advice I give, and I heard it phrased beautifully by a guy named Eric Resnick, who runs the largest private equity firm for travel and leisure, was recently on our show. He was told early on, combine your vocation with your avocation, which is just a thoughtful way of saying, do what you love.</p><p> I think that&#39;s general.</p><p> The problem with finance and alternative investments I would give advice that Howard Marks gives, which is if you want to have a great career in this space, start 30 years ago.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s great. I love Howard.</p><p> And our final question, what do you know about the world of investing today? You wish you knew 25, 30 years ago when you were first getting started.</p><p> SEIDES: I think the importance of people. We&#39;re talking about governance and decision-making and it was something that David Swensen taught me early on. But you have to go through people in difficult times, experiencing good and bad behavior in those times to really understand that ultimately active management is a people business.</p><p> And yes, you have to have all the investment discipline and all the rigor that goes into that, but they are human beings that are making decisions and that evaluating people as a frame for how you think about where you want to allocate your capital is probably the single most important thing you can do.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really fascinating stuff, Ted. Thank you for being so generous with your time.</p><p> We have been speaking with Ted Seides. He is the founder of Capital Allocator and the author of “Capital Allocators, How the World&#39;s Elite Money Managers Lead and Invest” and the host of the “Capital Allocators” podcast.</p><p> If you enjoy this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the previous 498 podcasts we&#39;ve done over the past eight years. You can find those at iTunes, Spotify, YouTube, wherever you find your favorite podcast. Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me on what&#39;s left of Twitter @ritholz. Follow all of the Bloomberg family of podcasts on Twitter @podcast.</p><p> I would be remiss if I did not thank the crack team that that helps put these conversations together each week, Justin Milner is my audio engineer. Atika Valbrun is my project manager. Sean Russo is my head of research. Paris Wald is my producer. I&#39;m Barry Ritholtz. You&#39;ve been listening to “Masters in Business” on Bloomberg Radio.</p><p></p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~ </p><p></p><p><iframe style="width: 100%; max-width: 660px; overflow: hidden; background: transparent;" src="https://embed.podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/masters-in-business/id730188152" height="450" frameborder="0" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" data-mce-fragment="1"></iframe></p><p><a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/08/transcript-ted-seides/">后记：泰德·塞德斯</a>首先出现在<a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">《大图片》</a>上。</p> ;
